import org.apache.spark.sql.Row
import org.apache.spark.sql.types.{IntegerType, StructType}
val PATH_TO_DATA = "/Users/harihar/Downloads/movie_metadata.csv"
val dfOrig = spark
    .read
    .option("header", true)
    .option("inferSchema", true)
    .option("ignoreLeadingWhiteSpace", true)
    .option("ignoreTrainingWhiteSpace", true)
    .option("nullValue", "Unknown")
    .csv(PATH_TO_DATA)
val numericalIndices = dfOrig
    .schema
    .fields
    .zipWithIndex
    .filter{case (value, index) => value.dataType == IntegerType}
    .map{case (value, index) => index}
    .toSet
val df = sqlContext.createDataFrame(dfOrig.rdd.map{ row =>
    Row.fromSeq(row.toSeq.zipWithIndex.map{ case (value, index) =>
        if (numericalIndices.contains(index) && value == null)
            0
        else
            value  
    })
}, StructType(dfOrig.schema))
df.schema.foreach(field => println(field.dataType + ": " + field.name))
df.createOrReplaceTempView("movies")

%md
My exploratory data analysis looks at whether the following fields seems to be related to the IMDB score.

## Color
I made a boxplot and found that the Null color is not predictive. However, Black and White movies tend to have a higher IMDB score than Color movies. I think this is because famous, classic movies are Black and White (e.g. 12 Angry Men, Dr. Strangelove, A Streetcar Named Desire, Seven Samurai). In addition, some famous movies that aren't actually Black and White have been put into that category (e.g. Forrest Gump).

So, Color does seem predictive.

## Director Name
I made a bar chart plotting median IMDB score vs. director and Number of Movies vs. director.

More prolific directors do not necessarily make better movies. Also, most directors in the dataset have made just a single movie. 

There is certainly variation in the median IMDB score among directors.

Finally, even the most prolific director in the dataset (Steven Spielberg) has made just 26 movies, which is about 0.5% of the movies in our dataset. Therefore, since each director makes a very small fraction of the movies in the database, it may not be useful to include the director as a feature.

## Actors (1, 2 and 3)
The same behavior occurs for actors. Even the most prolific actor (Robert Di Nero) has only made 49 movies, which is about 1% of the database. Thus, we won't use the actor.

## Number of Critics
Plotting a scatterplot of score vs. number of critics shows that highly rated movies tend to have more critics. This makes sense because highly rated movies are probably more well known and thus receive more critics.

## Duration
Made another scatterplot. There seems to be a weak trend where longer movies tend to have higher score. This trend is so weak (R^2 < 0.05), however, that duration probably is not very predictive.

## Facebook Likes
Another scatterplot. There are a few directors with many Facebook likes (e.g. Christopher Nolan, Martin Scorsese) who have higher IMDB scores. However, in large part, the relation between director facebook likes and score seems to be weak (R^2 < 0.05). A similar phenomenon occurs when we plot score vs. actor likes.

## Gross
There's a weak trend where movies that gross higher also score higher.

## Number of Users who Reviewed
There's a moderate trend where more user reviews predicts higher score.

## Number of Users who Voted
There's a moderate trend where more user votes predicts higher score.

## Budget
Budget is very weakly associated with score.

## Content Rating
I made a boxplot and there's a good deal of variation in score vs. content rating.

## Title Year
There's a moderate trend where older movies tend to have higher scores.

## Language
There's great variation in score by language. Maybe that's just because the database includes few movies from non-English languages.

## Country
Mapping median score, we see that countries have very different median scores.

// Attempt to fit with linear regression.
import org.apache.spark.ml.regression.{LinearRegression, LinearRegressionModel}
import org.apache.spark.ml.tuning.{CrossValidator, ParamGridBuilder}
import org.apache.spark.ml.evaluation.RegressionEvaluator
import org.apache.spark.sql.{DataFrame, Dataset, Row}

val labelCol = "imdb_score"
val featuresCol = "features"
val predictionCol = "prediction"

def makeEvaluator() = {
    new RegressionEvaluator()
        .setLabelCol(labelCol)
        .setPredictionCol(predictionCol)
}

def makeLrModel(train: DataFrame, 
                    test: DataFrame, 
                    featureVectorNames: Option[Array[String]] = None) = {
    val lr = new LinearRegression()
        .setMaxIter(20)
        .setLabelCol(labelCol)
        .setFeaturesCol(featuresCol)
        
    val eval = makeEvaluator()
    
    val paramGrid = new ParamGridBuilder()
        .addGrid(lr.regParam, Array(0.1, 0.3, 0.5))
        .addGrid(lr.elasticNetParam, Array(0.1, 0.3, 0.8))
        .build()
     
    val lrCv = new CrossValidator()
      .setEstimator(lr)
      .setEvaluator(eval)
      .setEstimatorParamMaps(paramGrid)
      .setNumFolds(3)
    
    val lrCvModel = lrCv.fit(train)
    val lrPredictions = lrCvModel.transform(test)
    
    if (featureVectorNames.isDefined)
        lrCvModel
            .bestModel
            .asInstanceOf[LinearRegressionModel]
            .coefficients
            .toArray
            .zip(featureVectorNames.get)
            .sortWith(_._1.abs > _._1.abs)
            .foreach{ case (coeff, value) => println(s"$value: $coeff")}
    lrPredictions
}
val lrPredictions = makeLrModel(train, test, Some(featureVectorNames)) 
lrPredictions.createOrReplaceTempView("lrPredictions")
